metadata.name: Particularization #31
metadata.description:
‚ÄúParticularization‚Äù is the seventh collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

All concepts can be viewed from different levels. You can focus on the details, leaving out the generalized result but understanding the finer points. Or you could emphasize the concept as a whole, comprehending it well overall but missing out on the specifics. It's impossible to choose both, you have to figure out which approach works best for each scenario.

metadata.name: V.Mountains #119
metadata.description:
V.Mountains is an abstract representation of the turbulence and chaos of our life.



The mountain is a symbol of the way that life is constantly in flux,

of the way that we are constantly trying to make sense of the world around us.



The mountain is a source of inspiration, a place of refuge, a source of strength.

It is a place where we can go to reflect on our lives, to find peace and solace.



The mountain is a symbol of hope.

It is a reminder that, no matter how dark and cold the world may be, there is always a chance for new beginnings.



The mountain is a symbol of the human spirit, and of our ability to persevere in the face of adversity.

It is a representation of our journey through life, with all of its ups and downs.

It is a reminder that, no matter how difficult the path may be,
we can always reach the summit if we are willing to put in the hard work.



Created in Vanilla Javascript.


S - to download image.


Libraries used:

noise.js by Joseph Gentle.
Javascript-Voronoi by Raymond Hill.

metadata.name: Emotions #14
metadata.description:
This is a collection inspired by the intense emotions I experienced while creating it.
It‚Äôs a combination of joy, anxiety, anger & hope all mixed on the canvas and visualized using p5js. I‚Äôm almost sure that if you look at these pieces you will find some of your own emotions in it.
From a technical standpoint, it is an exploration of flow fields and different color blending techniques.

Controls (in live view):

- press 'd' to generate 3000x4000 image
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view

metadata.name: ombromanie #72
metadata.description:
‚ÄúHow hands can create the vision that germinates in my mind? And what if the vision directly sprouts from the hands instead of the mind‚Äù, the artist asks.
‚ÄúIs the vision thrown through the shadow of the hands, or is the shadow hands the vision itself?‚Äù, the magician responds.
As an attempt to add a line to this whimsical dialogue, I dropped shadows to cast visions. To my great surprise, the artist and the magician blent into each other‚Ä¶

- - -

‚ÄúOmbromanie‚Äù refers to the art of creating images made by hand shadows. The word and the art (also called ‚Äúshadowgraphy‚Äù) was popularized by french magician F√©licien Trewey in the XIXth century. Sure the shadow art is not so popular nowadays, but it still shares with generative art part of the same mystery and magic. The code projects shapes and colors on a screen to create images; the hands project a shadow on a curtain to create figures.

‚ÄúOmbromanie‚Äù was conceived as a curtain where articulated hands (or better, shadow of hands) throw a firework of shapes, creating a wide range of random compositions. I heard the magician words and I did implement five features for this magical trick:
- the curtain can be entire or hemmed,
- the image oriented the right way up or upside-down,
- one or two hands can be used for the invocation,
- the phatasmagoria reveals itself as syzygy or chaos,
- and climax is reached through twelve ways.
Hands are always present, but in extremely rare cases they could vanish behind the curtain‚Ä¶   

- - - 

This project uses twelve custom color palettes ‚Äì the climaxes.
Ten are inspired after works or body of works by well known generative artists. A kind of tribute for the constant inspiration and creativity of the magicians-artists.
- ‚ÄúHollow‚Äù by @jMarkusiewicz
- ‚ÄúGarden, Monoliths‚Äù by @zancan
- ‚ÄúUninhabitable‚Äù by @pointline_
- ‚ÄúMimizu‚Äù by @qubibien
- ‚Äúaether:Astral Loom‚Äù by @lisaorthstudio
- ‚Äúgestalt‚Äù by @Yazid
- ‚ÄúPerpendicular Inhabitation‚Äù (night) by @StudioYorktown
- ‚ÄúAnaverse‚Äù by @anaglyph_ic
- ‚ÄúTake wing‚Äù by @mwiederrecht
- ‚Äúcontrapuntos‚Äù by @msoriaro
The eleventh palette is named ‚Äúfakewhale‚Äù(@fakewhale_xyz), who, months ago, encouraged me to learn and try code to create generative works. Special thanks to them for the support and dialogue.
The twelfth palette refers to my first long form generative project called ‚Äùth√©ba√Øde‚Äù.

- - -

A small word about the ‚Äúphatasmagoria‚Äù part, which tells about the invisible thread that sews my artistic approach. This part is a modified and extended code I used to create a set of six pieces titled ‚ÄúSketches for unreliable structure‚Äù (Objkt, December 2022). And those were already an echo from a selection of digital (but not coded) works from ‚ÄúThe Queue Structure‚Äù project (Objkt, since May 2022). Finally, The Queue Structure itself was a visual laboratory nourished by my previous practice of abstraction in the tangible world (drawing, collage, monotype, engraving). 

- - -

Press ‚Äús‚Äù in live mode to save the work as a PNG (default 2000 √ó 2000 px).
Add to the URL ‚Äù&size=n‚Äù (number from 3 to 10) to render an image at higher resolution (from 3000 px to 10000 px). It may last for high numbers.
We recommend the use of Chrome browser in order to render properly the texture.

Made with p5js | 2023
Png |¬†2000 √ó 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.net

metadata.name: Moonlit Mountains #72
metadata.description:
In this work I tried to depict variations of a forested mountain landscape lit by moonlight. The trees, mountains, sky, clouds, moon, stars, everything is generated 100% with code using random numbers from various distributions.

There are many features that are randomly chosen and used to guide the composition. The values for each feature are not equally probable. Some rare features are a Blue Moon (5%) and Shooting Star (15%).

Features:

Steepness: 1 -> 10 (larger values are steeper)

Big Trees: 0 -> 3  (large trees in foreground)

Tree Density: Low, Medium, High

Moon Phase: New, Waning Crescent, Waning Quarter, Full, Waxing Quarter, Waxing Crescent

Moon Size: Small, Medium, Large, Very Large

Fog Level: Low, Medium, High, Very High

Cloud Level: None, Low, Medium, High, Very High

Stars: None, Low, Medium, High, Very High

Prevailing Winds: Leftward, Neutral, Rightward

Moon Color: Blue, Red, Orange, Yellow, Silver

Shooting Star: true, false

Sky Color: many

metadata.name: The Streamline #140
metadata.description:
Form, an essential aspect in architectural design, refers to the shape, structure and arrangement of spaces or objects. Witnessing how forms work in a space can also be a transcendental experience, where one can sense the presence of a form, not only seeing it.

As there are many ways to create it, Form can appear as an internal structure, as an external shape of a two dimensional plane that envelopes a three dimensional mass, or a repetition of a two dimensional shape that stacks on an axis and moves to a certain direction. With so many ways to create shape, there is no law dictating that shape has to be rigid. And this is where Milunic and Gehry's design for the Dancing House comes in as an inspiration for this work.

A change in the political axis from one of a regime to a parliamentary democracy was what influenced the architects to juxtapose two different energies together. With its dynamic and static shapes in tandem, Dancing House is one iconic proof that form can also be pliable and animated.

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.
